          "title": "The theological hinge — why Pharaoh still stands (9:13-16)",
          "body": "The divine speech that opens the seventh plague unit is the most important passage in the chapter and arguably the theological center of the entire plague narrative. YHWH does not merely threaten; He explains. Verse 14 states the confrontational purpose: 'that you may know that there is no one like Me in all the earth.' YHWH's incomparability — not merely His superiority to Egypt's gods but His absolute uniqueness — is what the plagues are designed to communicate. Verse 15 is a parenthetical that staggers: God could have destroyed Pharaoh already. The power was available, the provocation was sufficient, the deed would have been just. Verse 16 is the theological turn: 'But indeed, for this reason I have allowed you to remain' — literally, 'I have caused you to stand.' Pharaoh's continued existence is an act of divine preservation for a declared purpose: to show God's power and to proclaim His name through all the earth. Paul quotes verse 16 verbatim in Romans 9:17 as a cornerstone argument for divine sovereignty in election. The implication is shattering: even the most defiant human resistance is enrolled, without its own consent, in the proclamation of YHWH's name."
